# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bandy-world-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bandy-world-cup/2016-bandy-world-cup] The **2016 Bandy World Cup** was the 44th annual Bandy World Cup and took place in Göransson Arena in Sandviken, Sweden, on 13-16 October 2016.
[src:bandy-world-cup/2016-bandy-world-cup] The teams invited to this year's cup were Sandvikens AIK, Bollnäs, Broberg, Edsbyn, Hammarby, Villa Lidköping, Vetlanda, IFK Vänersborg, and Västerås SK from Sweden, Baykal-Energiya, Yenisey, Dynamo Moscow, and SKA-Neftyanik from Russia, Akilles and Botnia-69 from Finland and Stabæk from Norway.
[src:bandy-world-cup/2016-bandy-world-cup] After initial group stage games, the tournament ends with a knock-out stage.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships] The **Aerobic Gymnastics World Championships** are the World Championships for aerobic gymnastics.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP **Aquabike World Championship** is a powerboating sports competition.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship is the premier class of jetski racing, founded in 1992.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Aquabike jetskis are personal watercraft vehicles purpose-built for racing and modified according to class.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship is organized and promoted by H2O Racing Ltd on behalf of the Union Internationale Motonautique (UIM), the governing body of powerboating and the exclusive entity recognized by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] This term refers to an Aquabike designed to be stood upon and is powered by rear jet propulsion with a completely closed system.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Skis, by definition, are the most demanding to ride as they require high fitness levels and great physical strength as well as agility in the legs and arms.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] According to the different degrees of modifications to the engine and bodywork, this type of Aquabike is used for three different categories: GP1, GP2 and Stock.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Another category (GP3) also exists in which younger drivers, between the ages of 11 and 14, compete.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Ski bikes are also used in the Freestyle category however this requires further structural changes to the size and motor, allowing the Ski to become considerably shorter in length, lighter in weight and able to perform better at low engine speeds.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Ski bikes are currently used in three different disciplines of the UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship: Closed Circuit, Parallel Slalom and Freestyle.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout refers to the largest and most powerful bikes in the Championship.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are designed for driving while seated and feature a saddle (located towards the front) and a rear jet or a completely closed propulsion system.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Runabouts are the most common jetski in the world, as they can also be used for recreational purposes.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] As with Ski bikes, Runabout bikes are used for three different racing categories: GP1, GP2 and Stock, according to the different degrees of modifications to the engine and bodywork.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are used in five different disciplines of the UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship: Closed Circuit, Offshore, Endurance, Jet Raid and Parallel Slalom.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Regulations require that the path does not exceed 1300m in length.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] The circuit is marked out by different coloured buoys: yellow (right turn) and red (left turn).
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Riders are required to complete a set number of laps (varies according to racing division) at the end of which, the chequered flag is waved by marshals.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] These races are held across long distances and require serious consideration to be taken for refuelling as this is usually done on land.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] The circuit is bordered by large buoys (visible from long distances) or by natural landmarks like coastline, lighthouses, islands, rocks, etc .
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Endurance races are held on long closed circuits.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] As endurance races are testing the long-term resistance of a rider and their bike, these races tend to last several hours and are more akin to a marathon as opposed to a sprint.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Given the long duration of the race, supplies are required in advance to ensure everything runs smoothly.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are used in endurance races.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] These races are spread over several stages.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Riders are required to travel long distances marked by checkpoints to complete the race.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] These races are often very time consuming as riders cover one expanse of water, and reach the coast on the other side, where their bike then has to be transported by land to the next race stage.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] This category is more of a competition than a race.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Riders are given a duration of three minutes to perform a rehearsed routine, one at a time.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] The stunts are evaluated by a team of five expert judges.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] The evaluation criteria are: quality, quantity and variety.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] The most common moves are Backflip, Barrel Roll, 360, Superman and Submarine.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Safety and security is of paramount importance during all the races and tests.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] Each member of the rescue team present at all races is required to have a certificate proving their ability to rescue and transport personal watercraft and injured riders.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] The support of the firefighters and patrol boats is essential as they ensure the immediate action in case of more serious accidents.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] On the ground, there is a medical team specialised in traumatology who are able to accompany the riders to the closest hospital to the race site.
[src:bandy-world-cup/aquabike-world-championship] In offshore racing, there is also a helicopter rescue service.
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] The **Archery World Cup** is a competition **outdoor**organized by World Archery, where the archers compete in four stages in four countries and the best eight archers of each category (from 2010, four archers during 2006–09) advance to an additional stage to contest the Archery World Cup Final.
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] It has received plaudits for its innovative approach to the sport, raising its profile and reach.
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] From 2013, the World Cup is broadcast live on Eurosport.
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] It carries sponsorship from Kia and Longines, which supports the annual Longines Prize of Precision for archery, for the "best male and female athletes that master bow and arrow through concentration, balance, accuracy, and skill".
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] The following venues have hosted stages of the World Cup Final.
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] The Longines Prize for Precision is awarded to the male and female archers who shoot the most 10s over the course of the competition at the end of the season.
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] It has been awarded since 2010 and is awarded to compound and recurve archers in alternate years.
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] Winners receive a trophy, watch and cash prize of 5,000 CHF.
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] The following table shows the total number of all medals (including stage and finals).
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] The following table shows the total number of individual medals (including stage and finals).
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] An **Indoor Archery World Cup** was inaugurated in 2010.
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] It is played in the off-season (November to February), with fewer stages and the final competed in Las Vegas.
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] In 2014, the stages were held in Marrakesh, Singapore and Telford.
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] 2019-2020 Indoor Archery World Series have 6 qualification and one final stage.
[src:bandy-world-cup/archery-world-cup] After 2018, the World Indoor Archery Championships were discontinued, leaving the Indoor Archery World Series as the premier championship in indoor archery.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] A 1,133-kilometer-long (704 mi) railway runs from Arkhangelsk to Moscow via Vologda and Yaroslavl, and air travel is served by the Talagi Airport and the smaller Vaskovo Airport.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] As of the 2021 Census, the city's population was 301,199.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The arms of the city display the Archangel Michael in the act of defeating the Devil.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Legend states that this victory took place near where the city stands, hence its name, and that Michael still stands watch over the city to prevent the Devil's return.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Vikings knew the area around Arkhangelsk as Bjarmaland.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Ohthere of Hålogaland told circa 890 of his travels in an area by a river and the White Sea with many buildings.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] This was probably the place later known as Arkhangelsk.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] According to Snorri Sturluson, Vikings led by Thorir Hund raided this area in 1027.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In 1989, an unusually impressive silver treasure was found by local farm workers by the mouth of Dvina, right next to present-day Arkhangelsk.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Most of the findings comprised a total of 1.6 kilograms (3.5 lb) of silver, largely in the form of coins.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Jewelry and pieces of jewelry come from Russia or neighboring areas.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The majority of the coins were German, but the hoard also included a smaller number of Kufan, English, Bohemian, Hungarian, Danish, Swedish and Norwegian coins.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] It is hard to place this find historically until further research is completed.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] There are at least two possible interpretations.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] It may be a treasure belonging to the society outlined by the Norse source material.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Generally such finds, whether from Scandinavia, the Baltic area, or Russia, are closely tied to well-established agricultural societies with considerable trade activity.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Alternatively, like the Russian scientists who published the find in 1992, one may see it as evidence of a stronger case of Russian colonization than previously thought.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In the 12th century, the Novgorodians established a monastery dedicated to Archangel Michael in the estuary of the Northern Dvina.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The main trade center of the area at that time was Kholmogory, located 75 kilometers (47 mi) southeast of Arkhangelsk, up the Dvina River, about 10 kilometers (6.2 mi) downstream from where the Pinega River flows into the Dvina.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Written sources indicate that Kholmogory existed early in the 12th century, but there is no archeological material of this period.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] It is not known whether the origin of this settlement was Russian, or if it goes back to pre-Russian times.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In the center of the small town (or Gorodok) that is there today is a large mound of building remains and river sand, but it has not been archeologically excavated.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The area of Arkhangelsk came to be important in the rivalry between Norwegian and Russian interests in the northern areas.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] From Novgorod, the spectrum of Russian interest was extended far north to the Kola Peninsula in the 12th century.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] However, here Norway enforced taxes and rights to the fur trade.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] A compromise agreement entered in 1251 which was soon broken.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In 1411, Yakov Stepanovich from Novgorod went to attack northern Norway.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] This was the beginning of a series of clashes.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In 1419, Norwegian ships with five hundred soldiers entered the White Sea.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The "Murmaners", as the Norwegians were called (cf.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Murmansk), plundered many Russian settlements along the coast, among them the Archangel Michael Monastery.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Novgorod managed to drive the Norwegians back.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] However, in 1478 the area was taken over by Ivan III and passed to the Grand Duchy of Moscow with the rest of the Novgorod Republic.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Subsequently, the English gave the name "St.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Nicolas Bay" to the sea now known as the White Sea.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Ivan the Terrible found out about this, and brokered a trade agreement with the ship's captain, Richard Chancellor.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Trade privileges were granted to English merchants in 1555, leading to the founding of the Company of Merchant Adventurers, which began sending ships annually into the estuary of the Northern Dvina.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Dutch merchants also started bringing their ships into the White Sea from the 1560s.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Scottish and English merchants also traded in the 16th century; however, by the 17th century it was mainly the Dutch that sailed to the White Sea area.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In 1584, Ivan ordered the founding of **New Kholmogory** (which would later be renamed after the nearby Archangel Michael Monastery).
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] At the time access to the Baltic Sea was still mostly controlled by Sweden, so while Arkhangelsk was icebound in winter, it remained Moscow's almost sole link to the sea-trade.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Local inhabitants, called Pomors, were the first to explore trade routes to Northern Siberia as far as the trans-Urals city of Mangazeya and beyond.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In December 1613, during the Time of Troubles, Arkhangelsk was besieged by Polish-Lithuanian marauders commanded by Stanislaw Jasinski (Lisowczyks), who failed to capture the fortified town.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In 1619, and again in 1637, fires broke out, and the entire city burned down.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In 1693, Peter the Great ordered the creation of a state shipyard in Arkhangelsk.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] A year later the ships *Svyatoye Prorochestvo* (Holy Prophecy), *Apostol Pavel* (Apostle Paul), and the yacht *Svyatoy Pyotr* (Saint Peter) were sailing in the White Sea.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] However, he also realized that Arkhangelsk would always be limited as a port due to the five months of ice cover, and after a successful campaign against Swedish armies in the Baltic area, he founded Saint Petersburg in May 1703.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Nonetheless, Arkhangelsk continued to be an important naval base and maritime centre in the Russian north.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In 1722, Peter the Great decreed that Arkhangelsk should no longer accept goods that amounted to more than was sufficient for the town (for so-called domestic consumption).
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] It was due to the Tsar's will to shift all international marine trade to Saint Petersburg.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] This factor greatly contributed to the deterioration of Arkhangelsk that continued up to 1762 when this decree was cancelled.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Arkhangelsk declined in the 18th century as the Baltic trade became ever more important.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Its economy revived at the end of the 19th century when a railway to Moscow was completed and timber became a major export.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The city resisted Bolshevik rule from 1918 to 1920 and was a stronghold of the anti-Bolshevik White Army.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The White Army was supported by an Allied intervention in which British, French, Italian, and American troops helped to defend against the Bolsheviks.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The Allied forces, led by British Lieutenant General Frederick Poole, suffered numerous set-backs and eventually withdrew from Russia.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Without Allied support, the poorly disciplined White Army quickly collapsed and the Bolsheviks entered Arkhangelsk on February 21, 1920.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Arkhangelsk was also the scene of the Mudyug concentration camp.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] During both world wars, Arkhangelsk was a major port of entry for Allied aid.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] During World War II, the city became known in West Europe as one of the two main destinations (along with Murmansk) of the Arctic convoys bringing supplies in to assist the Soviet Union.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] During Operation Barbarossa, the German invasion of the Soviet Union in 1941, Arkhangelsk was one of two cities (the other being Astrakhan) selected to mark the envisioned eastern limit of German control.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] This military operation was to be halted at this A–A line, but never reached it, as the German armies failed to capture either of these two cities and also failed to capture Moscow.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Arkhangelsk was also the site of Arkhangelsk ITL, or the Arkhangelsk Labour Camp, in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Today, Arkhangelsk remains a major seaport, now open year-round due to improvements in icebreakers.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The city is primarily a center for the timber and fishing industries.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] On March 16, 2004, 58 people were killed in an explosion at a nine-storey apartment building in the city.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Arkhangelsk is the administrative center of the oblast and, within the framework of administrative divisions, it also serves as the administrative center of Primorsky District, even though it is not a part of it.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] As an administrative division, it is, together with five rural localities, incorporated separately as the **city of oblast significance of Arkhangelsk**—an administrative unit with the status equal to that of the districts.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] As a municipal division, the city of oblast significance of Arkhangelsk is incorporated as **Arkhangelsk Urban Okrug**.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Arkhangelsk is the final destination of Northern Railway.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In addition, the city is host to two airports, Vaskovo Airport and Talagi Airport where they host the 2nd Arkhangelsk United Aviation Division and Smartavia Airline, respectively.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] M8 highway provides a direct link to Moscow, Yaroslavl and Severodvinsk, the administrative center of the oblast.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Local public transit is provided by buses and minibuses called *marshrutkas*.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Until 2004 there were also trams, and until 2008, trolleybuses.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Arkhangelsk was home to Pomorsky State University and Arkhangelsk State Technical University which merged with several other institutions of higher learning in 2010 to form the Northern (Arctic) Federal University.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Arkhangelsk is home to the Northern State Medical University, Makarov state Maritime Academy, and a branch of the All-Russian Distance Institute of Finance and Economics.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Mikhail Lomonosov came from a Pomor village near Kholmogory.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] A monument to him was installed to a design by Ivan Martos in 1829.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] A monument to Peter the Great was designed by Mark Antokolsky in 1872 and installed in 1914.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] After its historic churches were destroyed during Joseph Stalin's rule, the city's main extant landmarks are the fort-like Merchant Yards (1668–1684) and the New Dvina Fortress (1701–1705).
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The Assumption Church on the Dvina embankment (1742–1744) was rebuilt in 2004.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In 2008, it was decided that the city's cathedral, dedicated to the Archangel Michael, which had been destroyed under the Soviets, would be rebuilt.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The foundation stone was laid in November 2008 by the regional Bishop Tikhon.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The cathedral, situated near the city's main bus station and river port, is expected to be completed and consecrated in 2019.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Another remarkable structure is the Arkhangelsk TV Mast, a 151-meter (495 ft) tall guyed mast for FM-/TV-broadcasting built in 1964.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] This tubular steel mast has six crossbars equipped with gangways, which run in two levels from the central mast structure out to each of the three guys.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] On these crossbars there are also several antennas installed.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] An unusual example of local "vernacular architecture" was the so-called Sutyagin House.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] This thirteen-story, 44-metre (144 ft) tall residence of the local entrepreneur Nikolay Petrovich Sutyagin was reported to be the world's, or at least Russia's, tallest wooden house.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Constructed by Sutyagin and his family over fifteen years (starting in 1992), without plans or a building permit, the structure deteriorated while Sutyagin spent a few years in prison on racketeering charges.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In 2008, it was condemned by local authorities as a fire hazard, and the courts ordered it to be demolished by February 1, 2009.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] On December 26, 2008, the tower was pulled down, and the remainder of the building was dismantled manually by early February 2009.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] An airstrip/dam/facility in Arkhangelsk was the fictional setting for a level in the 1997 hit videogame *Goldeneye 007*.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The Russian North, and, in particular, the area of Arkhangelsk, is notable for its folklore.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Until the mid-20th century, fairy tales and *bylinas* were still performed on the daily basis by performers who became professionals.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Starting from the 1890s, folkloric expeditions have been organized to the White Sea area and later to other areas of the Arkhangelsk Governorate in order to write down the tales and the *bylinas*, especially in Pomor dialects.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] In the 1920s, mostly due to the efforts of Anna Astakhova, these expeditions became systematic.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] By the 1960s, the performing art was basically extinct.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] These folkloric motives and fairy tales inspired the literary works of Stepan Pisakhov and Boris Shergin, who were both natives of Arkhangelsk.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Arkhangelsk experiences a subarctic climate (Köppen climate classification *Dfc*), with long (November–March), very cold winters and short (June–August), mildly warm summers.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] More extreme climates at this high latitude – such as Fairbanks, Alaska or Oymyakon, Sakha Republic – have much colder winters than Arkhangelsk, indicating that there is still significant moderation from the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Snowfall during winter is heavy, while summers are very rainy.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Precipitation is very reliable year round.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] According to the 2021 Census, Arkhangelsk has a population of 301,199 people, which makes it the 68th largest city in Russia.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Bandy is the biggest sport in the city and is considered a national sport in Russia.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Vodnik, the local team, plays in a 10,000 capacity home arena, and have won the Russian championships nine times (1996–2000 and 2002–2005).
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] Arkhangelsk has hosted the Bandy World Championship twice, in 1999 and 2003.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The 2011–2012 season Russian Bandy League final was played here on March 25, 2012.
[src:bandy-world-cup/arkhangelsk] The 2016 Youth-17 Bandy World Championship was played in Arkhangelsk between January 28 and 31.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-billiards-world-championship] The **Artistic Billiards World Championship** is a carom billiards tournament in the discipline of artistic billiards, organized by the Confédération International de Billard Artistique.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-billiards-world-championship] Raymond Steylaerts of Belgium won the tournament six times, more than any other player.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-billiards-world-championship] The winners have mainly been European, and more commonly Belgian.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The **Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** are the world championships for artistic gymnastics governed by the Fédération Internationale de Gymnastique (FIG).
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The first edition of the championships was held in 1903, exclusively for male gymnasts.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Since the tenth edition of the tournament, in 1934, women's events are held together with men's events.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The FIG was founded in 1881 and was originally entitled FEG (Fédération Européenne de Gymnastique), but changed its name in 1921, becoming the Fédération Internationale de Gymnastique (FIG); this name change roughly correlates with the actual naming of the World Championships.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Although the first such games were held in 1903, they were not initially entitled the 'World Championships'.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The first competition ever actually referred to as a 'World Championships' at the time was a competition held in 1931 that, while referred to in an official FIG publication as the "First Artistic Men's World Championships", often seems to go ignored by various authorities in the sport.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The championships prior to the 1930s, beginning back in 1903, would eventually be recognized, retroactively, as the World Championships.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Additionally, repeat World All-Around Champion from 1909 and 1913, Marco Torres was also French-Algerian as he was born in Sidi Bel Abbès.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Perhaps the first African delegation was the Egyptian one which offered forth a full male team at the 1950 World Championships in Basel.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] By the time of these World Championships, a total of 60 male athletes from 6 countries and 53 female athletes from 7 countries comprised the competitive field.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] By the 2013 World Championships, the competition had grown to include 264 men from 71 countries and 134 women from 57 countries.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] As of 2023, over fifty editions of the championships have been staged, and over fifty countries have earned medals in artistic gymnastics events.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The most successful nation, both in gold medal results and total number of medals, is the former Soviet Union (not including medals from its successor states), and China is the second.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The United States is the third most successful country in gold medal results while Japan is the third in total number of medals.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Since the fall of the Iron Curtain, the traditional powerhouses in men's and women's individual still had expressive results: Russia, Belarus, Ukraine, China, United States, Japan, and Romania.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The last two decades were marked by increasing results from two emerging powers: Great Britain and Brazil and at the same period a big decrease in results from Belarus, Romania and Ukraine.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] However, this cycle was broken in 2021, when the COVID-19 pandemic led to the 2020 Summer Olympics to be delayed by one year, the edition scheduled for that year was not cancelled.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] While the Games were held between July and August 2021, the World Championships was allocated to the end of the same year.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] † The FIG (now World Gymnastics) in their 125-year anniversary publication, whereas pre-World War I editions of these championships are concerned, credits the teams and athletes from the Bohemian/Czech lands, then part of Austria-Hungary, as belonging to Czechoslovakia.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] †† There seems to be a history of inconsistency from the FIG's publications regarding whether these 1931 games are considered to be a World Championships.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Last updated after Day 7 of the 2025 World Championships.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Early events such as the 1913 and 1911 championships were purely team events without any individual awards, individual scores were only introduced in 1922, with the first all-round individual men's champion being recognised in that year.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Similarly the first women's championship in 1934 only had medals being awarded to teams, not individuals.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Individual "medals" for these events were therefore only recognised retrospectively and weren't awarded at the time.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Similarly, until 1921 FIG was known as the *European* Gymnastics Federation (*FEG*) and its events were not world championships as such.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] This brief biographical treatment was published at least as far back as 14 January 2017 on the official Facebook website of his alma mater in a photograph album, begun on 29 November 2016, containing other such brief biographical treatments of its notable alumni.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Boldface denotes active artistic gymnasts and highest medal count among all artistic gymnasts (including those not included in these tables) per type.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Few non-primary sources state that at the 1938 World Artistic Gymnastics Championships, in Prague, Vlasta Děkanová of Czechoslovakia won 2 or 3 golds on multiple apparatuses.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The only primary source on the subject, a book officially released by the International Gymnastics Federation containing the results of the World Championships from 1903 to 2005, informs that medals were distributed only in the team all-around event and in the individual all-around event.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Therefore, according to official reports, Děkanová's official number of gold medals is four, two in individual all-round (1934 and 1938) and two in team events (1934 and 1938) - not six or seven.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Only nations with medals in five or more events are listed.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Positions below third place are not taken into account.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Results for Germany and West Germany have been combined.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Only nations with medals in three or more events are listed.
[src:bandy-world-cup/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Positions below eighth place are not taken into account.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] The **Bandy World Cup** is an international bandy competition played in Sweden at the beginning of the bandy season every year, in autumn.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] The participating teams qualify based on their results in the previous bandy season.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] The World Cup is not played by national teams but is for bandy clubs from around the world, and should therefore not be confused with the Bandy World Championship.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] It is usually considered to be "the world championship for clubs".
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] The tournament has been dominated by the Swedish and Russian teams.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] The Bandy World Cup was held every year in Ljusdal in Sweden from 1974 to 2008, at the start of the bandy season in autumn.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] From 2009 it has been played indoors in Sandviken because Ljusdal was waiting for an indoor arena.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] The outdoor ices were too unpredictable because of the weather this time of the year, so for the 2009 cup the Federation of International Bandy demanded the cup should be played indoors.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] It was first decided to move the cup temporarily to Sandviken for two years, but when Ljusdal still had no indoor arena, a contract was made between FIB and Sandviken to host the cup in Sandviken up to and including 2013.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] It was agreed that if there was an indoor arena in Ljusdal in 2014, Ljusdal may apply to host the cup again.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] The tournament was first held in 1974 and has been called the World Cup since 1980.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] The full name of the cup has changed over the years, partly because of different sponsors.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] The first two years it was called DAF-cupen, then Dex-cupen 1976–1979 and Dex World Cup 1980–1983.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] 1984–1985 it was simply called World Cup Ljusdal.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] 1986 SJ became sponsors, so it was SJ World Cup 1986–1998.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] Then Ljusdal World Cup until 2001 and since 2002 it has been known as the Bandy World Cup, in 2005 additionally as Polar Bandy World Cup, since 2006 as ExTe World Cup Bandy.
[src:bandy-world-cup/bandy-world-cup] There is also a Bandy World Cup Women for women's teams.
